{"title_page": "Barton in the Beans", "text_new": "{{short description|Hamlet in Leicestershire, England}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Barton-in-the-Beans\n| country = England\n| region = East Midlands\n| shire_district = [[Hinckley and Bosworth]]\n| shire_county = [[Leicestershire]]\n| post_town = NUNEATON\n| postcode_area = CV\n| postcode_district = CV13\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.65|N|1.42|W}}\n| constituency_westminster = [[Bosworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Bosworth]]\n| static_image_name = Barton in the Beans, approaching from the south - geograph.org.uk - 794967.jpg\n| static_image_caption = Entrance to the village\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:Barton in the Beans, Baptist chapel - geograph.org.uk - 794972.jpg|thumb|Baptist chapel]]\n'''Barton in the Beans''' is a [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the [[Hinckley and Bosworth]] district of [[Leicestershire]], England and forms part of the [[Shackerstone]] [[civil parish]]. There are no shops or pubs here, only a [[Baptist]] Church and a [[post box]]. It was in the 18th century an important centre for the [[New Connexion of General Baptists|Baptist Church]] and the minister at Barton was the notable clockmaker Samuel Deacon (1746-1816). The population ca. 1830 was 177.\n\nOne of the earliest mentions of this place is in the [[Domesday Book]] where it is listed amongst the lands given to [[Hugh de Grandmesnil]]<ref name = \"Domesday\">''Domesday Book: a Complete Transliteration''. London: Penguin, 2003; p. 656 {{ISBN|0-14-143994-7}}</ref> by the [[William I of England|King]] (the land required half a plough and there were {{convert|2|acre|m2}} of meadow). During the Middle Ages the land passed through many hands including several members of the family of Hastings.\n\n==Toponymy==\nBarton is one of many places in England with this name: both this Barton and [[Barton in Fabis|that in Nottinghamshire]] were once known as \"Barton-in-Fabis\" but that is no longer used for the Leicester Barton.<ref>Firth, J. B. (1926) ''Highways and Byways in Leicestershire''. London: Macmillan; pp. 420-422</ref> In Domesday Book both are just 'Bartone' and later usage has varied (the meaning of Barton in both cases is probably 'grange' i.e. an outlying farm within an estate).\n\nA popular saying in the county is \"Shake a Leicestershire man by the collar and you may hear the beans rattle in his belly\": the author John Benjamin Firth quotes this from a contributor to ''[[Magna Britannia]]'', 1820.<ref>Firth, J. B. (1926) ''Highways and Byways in Leicestershire''. London: Macmillan; p. 422</ref> Leicestershire was once noted for cultivating the broad bean ([[Vicia faba]])<ref>Evans, Arthur Benoni (1881) ''Leicestershire Words, Phrases, and Proverbs''. London: Tr\u00fcbner & Co.; p. 101, p. 299 \"Bean-belly: an epithet of Leicestershire\"</ref> and in this way the bean has been perpetuated in place-names.\n\n==Samuel Deacon, Baptist pastor and clockmaker==\nDeacon settled at Barton ca. 1765 and set up in business as a clockmaker. His workshop was preserved by his successors and after many years of continuous use is now in the collections of the [[Newarke Houses Museum|Leicester Museum]]. He was a leader of the [[General Baptists]] sect and the author of many works, including his autobiography.<ref>Nichols, John (1795-1815). ''History of the County of Leicester''. Vol. 3. London: John Nichols</ref><ref>''Leicestershire Clocks [and] the Deacon Workshop''; compiled by the Earl Shilton Old Clock Club, 2002-05. Issue 2: 2005. CD-ROM</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\nJohn Goodman (born 1765) was a [[Baptist]] preacher who hired out [[leech]]es for [[bloodletting]]. The leeches came from lakes in [[Cheshire]] and [[North Wales]] through which Goodman would wade with bare legs.<ref>Palmer, Roy (1985) ''The Folklore of Leicestershire and Rutland''. Wymondham, Leicestershire: Sycamore Press; p.74</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n11.my journal by oly the great Hughes\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Barton in the Beans}}\n* {{oscoor gbx|SK396063}}\n* {{OpenDomesday|SK3906|barton-in-the-beans|Barton &#91;-in-the-Beans&#93;}}\n\n{{coord|52.65|N|1.42|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(SK396063)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n[[Category:Hamlets in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Hinckley and Bosworth]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hamlet in Leicestershire, England}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Barton-in-the-Beans\n| country = England\n| region = East Midlands\n| shire_district = [[Hinckley and Bosworth]]\n| shire_county = [[Leicestershire]]\n| post_town = NUNEATON\n| postcode_area = CV\n| postcode_district = CV13\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.65|N|1.42|W}}\n| constituency_westminster = [[Bosworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Bosworth]]\n| static_image_name = Barton in the Beans, approaching from the south - geograph.org.uk - 794967.jpg\n| static_image_caption = Entrance to the village\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:Barton in the Beans, Baptist chapel - geograph.org.uk - 794972.jpg|thumb|Baptist chapel]]\n'''Barton in the Beans''' is a [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the [[Hinckley and Bosworth]] district of [[Leicestershire]], England and forms part of the [[Shackerstone]] [[civil parish]]. There are no shops or pubs here, only a [[Baptist]] Church and a [[post box]]. It was in the 18th century an important centre for the [[New Connexion of General Baptists|Baptist Church]] and the minister at Barton was the notable clockmaker Samuel Deacon (1746-1816). The population ca. 1830 was 177.\n\nOne of the earliest mentions of this place is in the [[Domesday Book]] where it is listed amongst the lands given to [[Hugh de Grandmesnil]]<ref name = \"Domesday\">''Domesday Book: a Complete Transliteration''. London: Penguin, 2003; p. 656 {{ISBN|0-14-143994-7}}</ref> by the [[William I of E